06482nam a22008415i 9781782382027DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20052005nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97817823820277 a10.1515/97817823820272doi  a(DE-B1597)637076  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0160002bisacsh00aThinking Utopia :bSteps into Other Worlds /ced. by Jörn Rüsen, Michael Fehr, Thomas W. Rieger. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMaking Sense of History ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tChapter 1 The Necessity of Utopian Thinking: A Cross-National Perspective -- tPART I POLITICS, CONSTRUCTION AND FUNCTIONS OF UTOPIAN THINKING -- tChapter 2 Aspects of the Western Utopian Tradition -- tChapter 3 Visions of the Future -- tChapter 4 Utopia, Contractualism, Human Rights -- tChapter 5 On the Construction of Worlds: Technology and Economy in European Utopias -- tPART II ARTIFICIAL WORLDS AND THE ‘NEW MAN’ -- tChapter 6 Bodies in Utopia and Utopian Bodies in Imperial China -- tChapter 7 Science, Technology and Utopia: Perspectives of a Computer- Assisted Evolution of Humankind -- tChapter 8 ‘Thinking about the Unthinkable’: The Virtual as a Place of Utopia -- tChapter 9 Natural Utopianism in Everyday Life Practice – An Elementary Theoretical Model -- tPART III MUSEUM AS UTOPIAN LABORATORY -- tChapter 10 Haunted by Things: Utopias and Their Consequences -- tChapter 11 Art – Museum – Utopia: Five Themes on an Epistemological Construction Site -- tChapter 12 Art, Science, Utopia in the Early Modern Period -- tChapter 13 Utopiary -- tPART IV UTOPIA AS A MEDIUM OF CULTURAL COMMUNICATION -- tChapter 14 The Utopian Vision, East and West -- tChapter 15 Trauma: A Dystopia of the Spirit -- tChapter 16 From Revolutionary to Catastrophic Utopia -- tChapter 17 The Narrative Staging of Image and Counter-Image: On the Poetics of Literary Utopias -- tChapter 18 Rethinking Utopia: A Plea for a Culture of Inspiration -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter the breakdown of socialist and communist systems in the East, it had become fashionable to declare the so-called "end of utopia" ("end of history," "end of narratives"). The authors of this volume do not share this view but think that it is time to rehabilitate utopian thought. The political concept of Utopia that has given its name to these transcendental projections onto the world has been too narrow to describe and analyze the moving forces of the mind perceiving human existence beyond reality. By broadening the perspectives of utopian studies, these essays enable the reader to reconstruct scholarly paradigms and strategies of utopian, complex and holistic thinking in modern cosmology, philosophy, sociology, in literary, historical and political sciences, and to compare traditions and ways of Western utopian thought to the practice in the East.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh1 aBraungart, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehr, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFehr, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKo, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKumar, Krishan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLongxi, Zhang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMainzer, Klaus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOevermann, Ul